{"cursor":"8764","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn quantum mechanics, a 'stationary state' is an eigenvector of the Hamiltonian,\nimplying the probability density associated with the wavefunction is independent\nof time. Quantum Mechanics Demystified, D. McMahon, Mc Graw Hill (USA),\n2006, ISBN(10) 0 07 145546 9 This corresponds to a quantum state with a\nsingle definite energy (instead of a probability distribution of different\nenergies). It is also called 'energy eigenvector', 'energy eigenstate', 'energy\neigenfunction', or 'energy [[Bra-ket notation|eigenket]]'. It is very similar to\nthe concept of atomic orbital and molecular orbital in chemistry, with some\nslight differences explained below.\n","linknr":332,"url":"Stationary_state","recorded":1362477373,"links":33,"instances":["physics","quantum_mechanics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Quantum mechanics"],"headings":["Introduction","Stationary state properties","Spontaneous decay","Comparison to \"orbital\" in chemistry","References","Further reading","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Qm_template_pic_4.svg/210px-Qm_template_pic_4.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/90/QuantumHarmonicOscillatorAnimation.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/e/5/ae533be9801b60d5f132129ff4cb1b25.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/4/b/84b1078f13d44a481454db09ed2df94f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/5/8/b584b3da8f265f251460b48a89a2e735.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/0/a/10adde06bf3199b610cd48d44fa11a41.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/4/b/84b1078f13d44a481454db09ed2df94f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/5/8/b584b3da8f265f251460b48a89a2e735.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/4/b/84b1078f13d44a481454db09ed2df94f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/5/8/b584b3da8f265f251460b48a89a2e735.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/0/a/10adde06bf3199b610cd48d44fa11a41.png","//u